<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-786-690  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 786 690.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  August 27 1990 v7 n34 p68(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Effective text management a must for firms in the 1990s. (AppliedIntelligence)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Martin, James.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Efficient management of unstructured textual information will be avital factor in the competitive business environment of the 1990s.andO;Information in offices today already overwhelms office workers,and 90 percent of text information currently exists in printedform while 10 percent is represented electronically.andP;  Wordprocessing places some internal documents in electronic form, butthe data is usually distributed as printed hard copy.andP;  Some firmsdisperse memos by electronic mail and download information fromon-line services.andP;  CD-ROM disks are another technology used todisseminate information in large quantities.andP;  Traditional database management systems are not suitable for managing text becausethey are designed for structured data and specify procedures forhandling data before the application is built.andP;  Emergingtechniques that address text-based information systems includeoptimized handling of variable and fixed-length fields in the samedatabase record and hypertext linking.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information Resources ManagementStrategic PlanningText CommunicationData ManagementInformation Overload.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Sources of textual office information. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>This is the first article in a series on text management and its influence inthe corporate environment.andM;The ability to manage textual information as efficiently as structured datawill become a new competitive edge for corporations in the 1990s.andP;  Users mustbe able to efficiently store, index and categorize text so it can beeffectively searched and retrieved, thus improving access to and use of thegrowing amount of information that threatens to overwhelm knowledge workers.andM;Information exists in a variety of forms -- such as data, word-processeddocuments, printed documents and images -- and must be portable amonggeographically dispersed knowledge workers.andP;  Typically, information iscopied, and the copies are distributed through interoffice mail, the PostalService, faxes and overnight delivery services.andP;  Electronic storage anddistribution of this information can reduce storage cost, provide moreefficient access to information and vastly improve retrieval potential.andM;This emphasis on efficiency is extremely important because information isalready overwhelming knowledge workers.andP;  They spend a large part of the dayreviewing the printed material that crosses their desks.andP;  Critical decisionsmust be made hourly about what to read, what to keep and what to file.andM;Thanks to word-processing systems, some internal documents already are inelectronic form, but these documents usually are printed, and copies are madeand distributed.andP;  Some companies use E-mail to disperse memos and progressreports.andP;  And information in the form of news articles, financial reports andmarket research is being downloaded from on-line information services.andM;CD ROM disks as well are being used to disseminate large amounts ofinformation.andP;  CD ROM information can also be downloaded for modification,such as inclusion into internal documents.andP;  Since these information sourcesare already in electronic form and thus machine-readable, they can easily bethe &quot;data&quot; for a text-management application.andM;Yet information sources in electronic form represent only about 10 percent ofthe information used by an organization.andP;  The other 90 percent is printed andnot immediately machine-readable.andP;  This is the critical mass -- the incomingbusiness correspondence, magazines, newspapers, external R and D reports, andreference and user manuals.andP;  Text-management applications will not succeed inmaximizing efficiency unless they address both electronic and non-electronicinformation sources.andM;Traditional database-management systems (DBMSs) have been used to address themanagement of text, but they are not the correct software tool because theyare oriented to structured data.andP;  Fields are fixed-length, and retrieval isvalue-oriented.andP;  For example, a request for data could be worded &quot;Select allrecords with amounts due greater than $1,000.&quot;andM;In addition, procedures for handling the data are specified before theapplication is built.andP;  Text is unstructured, and lengths are variable.andO;Retrieval is usually oriented to content.andP;  Users must be able to browsethrough a text collection.andP;  A traditional DBMS cannot adapt to thesecapabilities.andM;The solutions can be found in new techniques that are emerging to addresstext-based information systems.andP;  These techniques, which complement existingdatabase technology, include optimized indexing methodologies, hypertextlinking, optimized handling of fixed- and variable-length fields in the samerecord, and natural-language processing.andM;The use of such technology will allow text to be organized into coherentstructures that can be queried and manipulated across networks; providenavigation of these electronic textual information systems, letting usersretrieve relevant information and derive knowledge from that information; andallow information (and knowledge) to be more easily and efficiently sharedamong work groups and across professional disciplines.andM;----------The concepts in this article are described in a new volume, Text Management,of The James Martin Report Series.andP;  For more information on this volume, call(617) 639-1958.andP;  For information on seminars, contact (in the United Statesand Canada) Technology Transfer Institute, 741 10th St., Santa Monica, Calif.andO;90402 (213) 394-8305.andP;  In Europe, contact Savant, 2 New St., Carnforth,Lancs., LA5 9BX United Kingdom (0524) 734 505.andO;</TEXT></DOC>